  <h2>Understanding Sonoma Wine</h2>
  <p>When it comes to sonoma wine, quality matters more than price. Our team of sommeliers has tasted hundreds of options to bring you these expert recommendations.</p>

<h2>History & Origins of Sonoma County Wine</h2>

<p>Sonoma County's winemaking legacy began in 1812 when Russian settlers established <strong>Fort Ross</strong> on the rugged coast, planting the region's first grapevines to support their colonial outpost. However, the true foundation of Sonoma's wine industry emerged in the 1850s when Hungarian immigrant <strong>Agoston Haraszthy</strong> founded Buena Vista Winery in 1857, earning him the title "Father of California Viticulture."</p>

<p>Haraszthy's revolutionary contributions included importing over 100,000 European vine cuttings from 300 different varieties, establishing Sonoma as California's experimental vineyard. His efforts proved that <strong>Sonoma's diverse microclimates</strong> could support premium European varietals, laying the groundwork for the region's reputation for quality over quantity.</p>

<h3>Pivotal Historical Moments</h3>

<p>The <strong>Prohibition era (1920-1933)</strong> devastated Sonoma's wine industry, with most vineyards converted to prune orchards or abandoned entirely. Recovery began slowly in the 1940s, but the real renaissance started in the 1960s when families like the <strong>Sebastianis</strong> (Sebastiani Vineyards, 1904) and <strong>Matanzas Creek Winery</strong> pioneered modern winemaking techniques.</p>

<p>A watershed moment came with the <strong>1976 Judgment of Paris</strong>, where Chateau Montelena's Chardonnay (sourcing grapes from Sonoma County) defeated prestigious Burgundies, putting Sonoma on the international wine map.</p>

<h3>Modern Recognition and Classification</h3>

<p>Sonoma County achieved federal recognition as an <strong>American Viticultural Area (AVA)</strong> in 1983, followed by the establishment of 18 sub-AVAs including prestigious regions like <strong>Russian River Valley</strong> (1983), <strong>Dry Creek Valley</strong> (1983), and <strong>Sonoma Coast</strong> (1987). Each AVA reflects distinct terroir characteristics shaped by maritime influence, elevation, and soil composition.</p>

<p>Today, Sonoma County encompasses over <strong>60,000 vineyard acres</strong> across 425 wineries, with sustainable farming practiced on 99% of vineyard land. The region has earned global recognition for its commitment to <strong>environmental stewardship</strong> while producing world-class Pinot Noir, Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon, and Zinfandel that rival the finest European wines.</p>

<h2>Terroir & Climate</h2>

<h3>Climate Dynamics</h3>
<p>Sonoma County's Mediterranean climate creates ideal conditions for premium viticulture, with warm, dry summers and cool, wet winters. Average temperatures range from 45-55°F in winter to 75-85°F during the growing season, though significant variation exists across the county's diverse geography. Annual rainfall averages 25-50 inches, concentrated between November and April, providing essential winter moisture while ensuring dry harvest conditions. The region enjoys approximately 2,600-2,800 sunshine hours annually, with vintage variation creating distinct wine profiles—cooler years like 2010 and 2011 produced wines with higher acidity and more restrained fruit, while warmer vintages such as 2014 and 2015 yielded riper, more concentrated expressions.</p>

<h3>Soil Composition and Wine Impact</h3>
<p>Sonoma's geological diversity spans millions of years, creating a mosaic of soil types that profoundly influence wine character. In <strong>Russian River Valley</strong>, Goldridge sandy loam provides excellent drainage while retaining sufficient moisture for Pinot Noir, contributing to the variety's signature bright acidity and elegant red fruit flavors. The <strong>Sonoma Coast's</strong> Franciscan Complex soils, rich in sandstone and shale, stress vines appropriately, concentrating flavors and creating the mineral backbone found in coastal Chardonnays and Pinot Noirs.</p>

<p><strong>Alexander Valley's</strong> alluvial benchlands contain gravelly loam over clay subsoils, ideal for Cabernet Sauvignon's deep root penetration, resulting in wines with structured tannins and concentrated dark fruit. Meanwhile, <strong>Dry Creek Valley's</strong> ancient seabed soils, composed of gravelly clay and volcanic ash, contribute to Zinfandel's characteristic spicy intensity and robust structure.</p>

<h3>Geographic Influences</h3>
<p>Elevation plays a crucial role across Sonoma's 1,600 square miles, from sea-level vineyards to mountain sites reaching 2,600 feet. Higher elevation vineyards in the <strong>Sonoma Mountain AVA</strong> experience greater diurnal temperature variation—often 40-50°F between day and night temperatures—preserving acidity while achieving full phenolic ripeness. South and southwest-facing slopes capture optimal sun exposure, particularly important for late-ripening varieties like Cabernet Sauvignon.</p>

<h3>Microclimate Factors</h3>
<p>The <strong>Petaluma Gap</strong> creates Sonoma's most distinctive microclimate, funneling cool Pacific air and fog inland through this low mountain pass. This marine influence moderates temperatures in western appellations, extending the growing season and creating the crisp acidity and bright fruit character synonymous with Sonoma Coast wines. The <strong>Russian River</strong> acts as a natural cooling corridor, with morning fog regularly penetrating 15-20 miles inland, creating ideal conditions for cool-climate varieties.</p>

<p>Conversely, eastern valleys like <strong>Knights Valley</strong> remain largely protected from marine influence, experiencing warmer temperatures that favor Bordeaux varieties, producing wines with riper fruit profiles and softer acidity. These microclimatic variations within short distances allow winemakers to craft distinctly different expressions from the same variety, showcasing Sonoma's remarkable terroir diversity.</p>

<h2>What Does Sonoma Wine Taste Like?</h2>

