<p><strong>Primary aromas</strong> showcase Sonoma's fruit-forward character: Russian River Pinot Noirs offer bright cherry, cranberry, and wild strawberry, while Alexander Valley Cabernets present cassis, blackberry, and dark plum. Sonoma Coast Chardonnays deliver precise citrus notes—Meyer lemon, lime zest, and green apple.</p>

<p><strong>Secondary aromatics</strong> from fermentation include the distinctive brioche and hazelnut from quality lees stirring in Chardonnays, plus that telltale "forest floor" earthiness in Pinot Noirs from wild yeast fermentation.</p>

<p><strong>Tertiary notes</strong> from aging reveal Sonoma's signature integration: vanilla and sweet spice from American and French oak, plus evolved characteristics like tobacco leaf, cedar, and dried herbs in reds, or honey and roasted nuts in aged Chardonnays.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Palate and Texture</h3>

<p>Sonoma wines exhibit exceptional balance between ripeness and acidity. The region's marine influence maintains crucial acidity levels—typically 6.0-6.5 g/L in reds and 6.5-7.5 g/L in whites. Tannins in premium reds are notably supple yet structured, thanks to extended hang time and careful extraction. Alcohol levels feel integrated rather than hot, even at 14-15% ABV, due to physiological ripeness achieved through Sonoma's long, mild growing season.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Distinctive Flavor Markers</h3>

<p>Look for Sonoma's signature mineral backbone—a chalky, wet stone quality from volcanic soils in Bennett Valley, or the distinctive "graphite" note from Mayacamas Mountains fruit. Premium examples show layered complexity: dark chocolate and espresso in Dry Creek Zinfandels, white pepper and garrigue herbs in Rhône varietals, and that distinctive "bay leaf" note in Alexander Valley Cabernets.</p>

<p><strong>Quality indicators</strong> include persistent finish length (45+ seconds), seamless oak integration, and the ability to reveal new flavors with each sip—hallmarks of Sonoma's world-class terroir expression.</p>

