<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master Sonoma's Microclimates for Selection</strong> - Choose Sonoma wines by understanding their specific AVAs: Russian River Valley excels with Pinot Noir and Chardonnay due to morning fog, Dry Creek Valley produces stellar Zinfandel from ancient vines on hillside vineyards, while Alexander Valley's warmer sites craft exceptional Cabernet Sauvignon. Look for estate bottlings from producers like Williams Selyem (Russian River) or Ridge (Dry Creek) to experience true terroir expression.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Sonoma Pinot Noir Cooler Than Napa Reds</strong> - Sonoma Pinot Noir, particularly from Russian River Valley and Sonoma Coast, shows best at 58-62°F rather than the typical 65-68°F for heavier reds. The cooler temperature preserves the wine's signature bright acidity and delicate red fruit flavors that define coastal Sonoma terroir, preventing the alcohol from overwhelming the wine's elegant structure.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Most Sonoma Chardonnay</strong> - Unlike heavy Bordeaux-style reds, Sonoma's cool-climate Chardonnays from producers like Kosta Browne or Littorai are crafted for immediate accessibility. These wines benefit from slight chilling (48-52°F) in the bottle rather than decanting, which can strip away the subtle mineral notes and ocean influence that make Sonoma Coast Chardonnay distinctive.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy Glasses for Sonoma Pinot Noir</strong> - The wide bowl of a Burgundy glass (like Riedel Vinum or Zalto Burgundy) concentrates the aromatic compounds in Sonoma Pinot Noir, especially the forest floor, cherry, and spice notes that develop from the region's Goldridge sandy loam soils. Standard Bordeaux glasses compress these delicate aromatics that make Russian River and Sonoma Coast Pinots special.</li>

  <li><strong>Age Sonoma Zinfandel Differently by Style</strong> - Old-vine Sonoma Zinfandels from Dry Creek Valley (like those from Ravenswood or Seghesio) can age 8-12 years thanks to their concentrated fruit and balanced acidity, while modern-style Zins from warmer sites peak within 3-5 years. Look for alcohol levels: wines under 15% ABV typically have better aging potential than higher-alcohol versions.</li>

  <li><strong>Drink Young Sonoma Sauvignon Blanc Within 2-3 Years</strong> - Sonoma's Sauvignon Blanc, particularly from cooler sites near the Pacific Ocean, showcases bright citrus and mineral character when consumed young. Unlike Loire Valley examples that can age decades, Sonoma's style emphasizes fresh fruit and crisp acidity that begins to fade after year three, making producers like Spottswoode or Merry Edwards best enjoyed soon after release.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Sonoma Cabernet by Producer Philosophy</strong> - Traditional Sonoma Cabernet from producers like Chateau St. Jean or Jordan (Alexander Valley) are crafted for earlier drinking (5-8 years), emphasizing food-friendliness over power. However, cult producers like Araujo or Screaming Eagle's Sonoma bottlings require 10-15 years to fully develop, similar to their Napa counterparts. Check the producer's style before cellaring.</li>

  <li><strong>Pair Sonoma Wines with Ocean-Influenced Cuisine</strong> - Sonoma's proximity to the Pacific Ocean creates wines with natural acidity and minerality that pair exceptionally with seafood and lighter proteins. Russian River Pinot Noir complements salmon and duck, while Sonoma Coast Chardonnay enhances Dungeness crab and oysters—pairings that wouldn't work as well with the richer, more powerful wines from inland Napa Valley.</li>
