<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Sonoma County and Napa Valley wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma County wines tend to be more diverse and food-friendly due to the region's varied microclimates and proximity to the Pacific Ocean, while Napa focuses heavily on Cabernet Sauvignon. Sonoma's cooler coastal influence creates wines with higher acidity and more restrained alcohol levels, particularly in regions like Russian River Valley and Sonoma Coast. You'll also find better value in Sonoma, with exceptional wines often costing 30-50% less than comparable Napa bottles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Sonoma AVA produces the best Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Russian River Valley and Sonoma Coast are widely regarded as Sonoma's premier Pinot Noir regions, with Russian River offering more approachable, fruit-forward styles and Sonoma Coast producing more mineral-driven, age-worthy wines. The cool fog from the Pacific Ocean and well-draining soils create ideal conditions for this finicky grape. Look for producers like Williams Selyem, Rochioli, and Hirsch Vineyards for benchmark examples of each style.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are Sonoma wines good for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Sonoma wines are excellent for beginners because they offer approachable styles across all price points with less intimidation factor than Napa. The region's diverse grape varieties mean you can explore everything from crisp Sauvignon Blanc to bold Zinfandel without breaking the bank. Start with Russian River Valley Pinot Noir, Dry Creek Valley Zinfandel, or Alexander Valley Chardonnay for classic Sonoma expressions that are both accessible and food-friendly.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why are Sonoma Zinfandels different from other regions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma's old-vine Zinfandels, particularly from Dry Creek Valley, offer more balanced acidity and restrained alcohol compared to Paso Robles or Lodi versions. The region's diverse soils and moderate climate prevent the jammy, over-ripe characteristics common in hotter regions. Historic vineyards like Monte Rosso and Bedrock produce complex, age-worthy Zinfandels with spice, minerality, and elegant structure that pairs beautifully with food.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What should I serve with Sonoma Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sonoma Pinot Noir's bright acidity and moderate tannins make it incredibly versatile with food, particularly salmon, duck, mushroom dishes, and aged cheeses. The wine's earthy undertones complement roasted vegetables and herb-crusted meats, while its fruit-forward nature pairs beautifully with cherry or berry-based sauces. Serve slightly chilled at 60-65°F to highlight the wine's elegant structure and complex aromatics.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long do Sonoma wines need to age?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Sonoma wines are designed to drink well upon release, though premium Cabernets from Alexander Valley and Pinot Noirs from Sonoma Coast can benefit from 3-5 years of cellaring. Sonoma Chardonnays typically peak within 2-3 years, while old-vine Zinfandels can age gracefully for 8-10 years. The region's balanced style means you won't need to wait decades like some Napa Cabernets, making them perfect for near-term enjoyment.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best value alternative to expensive Sonoma wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For similar coastal-influenced styles at lower prices, look to Mendocino County's Anderson Valley for Pinot Noir and Chardonnay, or Santa Barbara County for comparable cool-climate expressions. Within Sonoma, seek out wines from newer or less famous producers in established AVAs rather than switching regions entirely. Brands like La Crema, Sebastiani, and Castle Rock offer excellent entry points to Sonoma terroir without the premium pricing of cult producers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Sonoma wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is assuming all Sonoma wines are similar when the region contains 18 distinct AVAs with dramatically different climates and soils. Many buyers also overlook Sonoma's exceptional white wines, focusing only on reds and missing outstanding Chardonnays and Sauvignon Blancs. Additionally, people often overpay for trendy producers when established family wineries like Seghesio, Rafanelli, and Ridge offer superior quality-to-price ratios with decades of proven track records.</p>
